      "role": "user",
      "content": "I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU. We're seeing a slow RAM exhaustion issue where the heap usage creeps up by about 15KB every 2-3 hours of operation. It's not crashing immediately, but it hits the limit mid-drive. I've looked at the main loops, but I can't find the culprit. \n\nCan you give me a systematic approach or a list of specific things to check in this snippet to track down where the allocation isn't being freed?\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data(const SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet == nullptr) return;\n\n    // Allocate buffer for processing\n    uint8_t* processing_buffer = new uint8_t[MAX_BUFFER_SIZE];\n    \n    if (validate_packet(packet)) {\n        copy_to_buffer(packet->data, processing_buffer, packet->size);\n        calculate_checksum(processing_buffer, packet->size);\n        update_ecu_state(processing_buffer);\n    } else {\n        log_error(\"Invalid packet received\");\n    }\n\n    // I think I'm handling the cleanup here, but the leak persists\n    delete[] processing_buffer;\n}\n\nvoid system_loop() {\n    while (system_running) {\n        SensorPacket* incoming = sensor_interface.poll();\n        if (incoming) {\n            process_sensor_data(incoming);\n            // Note: sensor_interface.poll() returns a pointer \n            // that needs to be managed elsewhere or here\n        }\n        wait_for_next_tick();\n    }\n}\n```",
